Anonymous Sat 09 Mar 2024 04:21:32 No.63884597 Report
Quoted By:
>>63884282
I mean, most endings tie everything up neatly, even rushed ones. I think the skill of being able to take the ending, and make it feel satisfying is something that takes a little more than just planning. It takes practice, and a good deal of scene engineering to really give an ending the oomph it needs. You can write
>Bob goes to the store to buy some milk
>He fights off some nuggets on the way
>Then he buys milk and goes home, the end
And there's a fifty fifty that the ending will suck. You could write a captivating intro as bob realizes he needs the milk, and then you could write a heart pounding, white knuckles fight scene with the muggers, but then Bob will buy the milk, and the story ends. If your story is linear, it's a bit easier, but if you write something episodic, I don't know how the hell you can do something satisfying.
Ultimately, it's a skill that needs to be honed through practice.

Eh, let's be fair here. Making realistic anthros work is not an easy task, you're bound to fuck it up one way or another. Especially when dealing with the face and whatnot.

The most straightforwardthing you could to would be to just paste an animal head on a humanoid body, but then, good luck trying to get it to be as expressive as a human face.

If you want more expressivity, you need something that combines human and animal traits. But to get that combination to work and not be uncanny, you'd need A LOT of knowledge about human and animal anatomy, about why that anatomy is the way it is, and even then it might not be enough.

There's a reason most furry art is highly stylized cartoony/animesque stuff. 2D gives you a lot of leeway.
